	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />A 611x lock CIC in the console reportedly won't work with a 319x key in the cartridge. Both 319x works, as does a 611x key with either lock revision.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Great Hierophant</b> [ Sun Jul 08, 2018 10:20 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES and Famicom Substitute ICs</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">ccovell wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Also note that the FDS RAM adaptor comes in a few varieties, some containing Fairchild and Sharp &quot;SRAMs&quot;.</div><br /><br />The FDS RAM Adapter always used standard 8K SRAM chips for the CHR-RAM, but always used DRAM for the PRG-RAM.  The early revisions of the FDS RAM Adapter come with four 16Kx4 DRAM chips, but later revisions come with a single chip that looks like an SRAM chip but functions like a DRAM chip.  This &quot;SRAM&quot; chip is not a common part but should be replaceable if you design a board to wire up the four standard DRAM chips appropriately.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>lidnariq</b> [ Mon Jul 09, 2018 1:30 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES and Famicom Substitute ICs</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The pinout of the 32KiB DRAM used in certain models is its own unique thing.<br /><br />But one should be able to do a small amount of rework to replace it with a conventional 32KiB SRAM. Many of the needed signals—CPUD[0..7], CPUA[7,13,14], R/W, M2, /ROMSEL—are already available from its footprint. The only question in my mind is whether one could use /CAS0, /CAS1, or /RAS, or whether one would have to manually decode the $6000-$DFFF region again.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Great Hierophant</b> [ Mon Jul 09, 2018 10:15 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES and Famicom Substitute ICs</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The pinout of the 32KiB DRAM used in certain models is its own unique thing.<br /><br />But one should be able to do a small amount of rework to replace it with a conventional 32KiB SRAM. Many of the needed signals—CPUD[0..7], CPUA[7,13,14], R/W, M2, /ROMSEL—are already available from its footprint. The only question in my mind is whether one could use /CAS0, /CAS1, or /RAS, or whether one would have to manually decode the $6000-$DFFF region again.</div><br /><br />You could decode the region, but I think the 2C33 already does that for you because those Column and Row Access Strobe signals should not be active unless the CPU is trying to read from or the 2C33 is trying to write to that memory area.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


